<sect1 id="awww" xreflabel="awww-&awww-version;">
  <?dbhtml filename="awww.html"?>

  <title>awww-&awww-version;</title>

  <indexterm zone="awww">
    <primary sortas="a-awww">awww</primary>
  </indexterm>

  <sect2 role="package">
    <title>Introduction to awww</title>

    <para>
      The awww (Answer to your Wayland Wallpaper Woes) package provides a
      powerful wallpaper daemon for Wayland, controlled at runtime.
    </para>

    &build-use-internet;

    <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
      <listitem>
        <para>
          Download (HTTP): <ulink url="&awww-download-http;"/>
        </para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>

    <bridgehead renderas="sect3">awww Dependencies</bridgehead>

    <bridgehead renderas="sect4">Required</bridgehead>
    <para role="required">
      <ulink url="&blfs-svn;/general/rust.html">Rustc</ulink>,
      <ulink url="&blfs-svn;/general/wayland.html">Wayland</ulink>, and
      <ulink url="&blfs-svn;/general/wayland-protocols.html">Wayland-Protocols</ulink>
    </para>

    <bridgehead renderas="sect4">Optional</bridgehead>

    <para role="optional">
      <ulink url="&blfs-svn;/multimedia/dav1d.html">dav1d</ulink>, and
      <xref linkend="scdoc"/> (to build the man pages)
    </para>

  </sect2>

  <sect2 role="installation">
    <title>Installation of awww</title>
    <para>
      Install awww by running the following
      commands:
    </para>

<screen><userinput>cargo build --release</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      To test the results, issue: <command>cargo test --release</command>.
    </para>

    <para>
      If you installed scdoc and wish to build the
      man pages, execute the following commands:
    </para>
<screen><userinput>./doc/gen.sh</userinput></screen>

    <para>
      Now, as the &root; user:
    </para>

<screen role="root"><userinput>install -vDm755 target/release/swww -t /usr/bin/ &amp;&amp;
install -vDm755 target/release/swww-daemon -t /usr/bin/</userinput></screen>

<!-- uncomment with next update -seal331 5th November 2025
<screen role="root"><userinput>install -vDm755 target/release/awww -t /usr/bin/ &amp;&amp;
install -vDm755 target/release/awww-daemon -t /usr/bin/ &amp;&amp;
ln -sfv /usr/bin/awww /usr/bin/swww &amp;&amp;
ln -sfv /usr/bin/awww-daemon /usr/bin/swww-daemon</userinput></screen> -->

    <para>
      If you wish to install shell completions, execute the relevant commands 
      for your shell(s) as the root user:
    </para>

<!-- awww also provides shell autocomplete files for a shell called "elvish".
     I have no clue what that shell is, let alone where does it store its
     autocomplete files. If someone figures that out feel free to add the
     install command for that shell here, the file is "completions/swww.elv".
     -seal331 4th November 2025 -->

<screen role="root"><userinput>install -vDm644 completions/swww.bash /usr/share/bash-completion/completions/swww
install -vDm644 completions/_swww /usr/share/zsh/site-functions/_swww
install -vDm644 completions/swww.fish /usr/share/fish/vendor_completions.d/swww.fish</userinput></screen>

<!-- uncomment with next update -seal331 5th November 2025
<screen role="root"><userinput>install -vDm644 completions/awww.bash /usr/share/bash-completion/completions/awww
install -vDm644 completions/_awww /usr/share/zsh/site-functions/_awww
install -vDm644 completions/awww.fish /usr/share/fish/vendor_completions.d/awww.fish</userinput></screen>
-->

    <para>
      If you built the man pages, install them as the &root; user:
    </para>

<!-- intentionally no futureproofing for renaming here because we use a
     wildcard -seal331 5th November 2025 -->
<screen role="root"><userinput>install -vDm644 doc/generated/* -t /usr/share/man/man1/</userinput></screen>

  </sect2>

  <sect2 role="commands">
    <title>Command Explanations</title>

    <para>
      <option>--features=avif</option>: Use this switch if you want to be able
      to display AVIF images (requires dav1d).
    </para>

  </sect2>

